{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The embedding vector produced for a given query string has the correct dimensionality for the vector database index.","required_reality_check_level":"Agentic","justification":"Unit tests on local shape logic can pass while production fails if the real embedding model (or configured model version) returns a different dimension than expected. This behavior depends on actual AI/ML output structure from the embedding call, so mocks can hide mismatch risk. Workflow is not required because this is a single model-output check, not a multi-agentic chain.","test_description":"Call the real embedding model with representative queries, fetch the active index dimension from the real/vector-db-backed config path, and assert exact dimension match before insertion/search.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.15,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0.68,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The similarity search returns results ordered by descending cosine similarity score.","required_reality_check_level":"System","justification":"This is about real vector search behavior and externally visible ranking order/score contract. In-process fakes can trivially return sorted fixtures and miss real DB/API ordering quirks, score normalization differences, or transport/serialization issues. Agentic is not required because this behavior does not depend on LLM judgment quality; it validates deterministic retrieval ordering.","test_description":"Issue real API requests against a live test vector index with known vectors and verify returned results are strictly non-increasing by cosine similarity score and IDs match expected nearest neighbors.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.03,"Integration":0.22,"System":0.67,"Agentic":0.06,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The LLM re-ranking step changes the order of at least some results compared to the raw similarity ranking when the query has nuanced intent.","required_reality_check_level":"Agentic","justification":"Correctness depends on real LLM decision quality (contextual relevance judgment), which stubs cannot validate. This is the deterministic-assertion trap: a mocked reranker can always reorder and falsely pass without proving the model handles nuance. Workflow is not required because this behavior targets one agentic decision point (reranking), not a multi-step agent pipeline correctness criterion.","test_description":"Run real reranking with nuanced query/result fixtures where lexical similarity conflicts with intent, compare pre/post order, and assert at least one meaningful positional change consistent with relevance expectations.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.04,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.82,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"A query with no close matches in the database returns an empty result set rather than low-relevance noise.","required_reality_check_level":"Agentic","justification":"Whether a query is truly 'no close match' depends on embedding/model-space behavior plus thresholding; fixture-only tests can hide real semantic-nearness noise from the model. So unit/integration around threshold logic alone is insufficient for confidence. Workflow is not required because the key risk is a single model-dependent retrieval judgment, not multi-agentic sequencing.","test_description":"Use real embeddings and real search on a corpus intentionally unrelated to selected queries, assert API returns empty results (or below-threshold rejection) and does not emit low-score items.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.12,"System":0.12,"Agentic":0.7,"Workflow":0.04}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The end-to-end latency from receiving the query to returning re-ranked results stays below 2 seconds for the median case.","required_reality_check_level":"Workflow","justification":"Latency target covers the full pipeline with multiple sequential stages, including multiple real agentic/model calls (embedding + LLM rerank) and external infra interactions. Lower-level tests cannot expose orchestration and cross-stage timing composition. This is explicitly a multi-step agentic end-to-end property.","test_description":"Run production-like end-to-end requests through the full stack (real model endpoints, real vector search path, reranking enabled), collect latency distribution over a representative query set, and assert median response time < 2.0s.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.0,"Integration":0.03,"System":0.18,"Agentic":0.24,"Workflow":0.55}}]}
